The "renormalization constant"  is a nonvanishing Poincare invariant and thus the cut-off function 
 is well defined. What is important, the field  is now massless and therefore vanishes not only at infinity but also at . 

Having the "out" fields we can compute their ("in"-)vacuum averages. The result is analogous to the standard one, but now the Fourier transform of the field involves the amplitude







 
and not  which would have occured in the irreducible formalism. The difference is subtle but of crucial importance since the property  can regularize the infrared divergence. In the irreducible case the radiation field produced by an accelerated pointlike charge involves the amplitude 
 which instead of vanishing blows up at . In the reducible case we obtain a regularization which eliminates the infrared divergence if the vacuum 
 is correctly chosen. The same concerns the average number of photons of the radiated field. Let us mention that the operators 
 appear also in reducibly quantized solutions of Maxwell equations with classical currents and thus regularize classical divergences. 

To conclude, the reducible representations seem to produce the cut-off functions in exactly those places one expects them to occur. This is a consequence of the RHS of CAR and CCR where instead of identities one finds  and . At the level of amplitudes and in thermodynamic limits one finds the effective rule , 
. The analogy to  renormalized fields(I am indebted to prof. H. Grosse for drawing my attention to this point during our discussion in Bialowieza 
whose CAR and CCR relations involve at RHS the renormalization constants  and  supplemented by cut-offs is probably not accidental. An argument in favor of our approach is that the RHS of CAR and CCR are Poincare covariant since 

